SIMPLE: ize
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: -ize
<hw>-ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> <pos>suff.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>-iser</ets>,
L. <ets>-izare</ets>, Gr. <?/.]</ety> <def>A verb suffix signifying
<sig>to make</sig>, <sig>to do</sig>, <sig>to practice</sig>; <as>as,
apolog<ex>ize</ex>, bapt<ex>ize</ex>, theor<ex>ize</ex>,
tyrann<ex>ize</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In the case of certain words the spelling with
-<xex>ise</xex> (after analogy with F. <xex>-iser</xex>) is the usual
form; as, catech<xex>ise</xex>, critic<xex>ise</xex>. With regard to
most words, however, which have this suffix there is a diversity of
usage, some authorities spelling -<xex>ise</xex>, others (as in this
book) -<xex>ize</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Izedi</ent>⟦br⟧
